    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "\nThis Commentary refers to: \u2018Coronavirus fulminant myocarditis saved with glucocorticoid and human immunoglobulin\u2019, by H. Hu et al., doi:10.1093/eurheartj/ehaa190.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "We would like to comment on the case study published in the European Heart Journal.1 The presented 37-year-old patient was admitted to hospital due to chest pain, dyspnoea, diarrhoea, coronavirus-associated pulmonary infection, pseudo ST-segment elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI) with normal coronary arteries, hypotension, and decreased left ventricular ejection fraction. The patient was successfully treated with methylprednisolone (200 mg/day, for 4 days), intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG; 20 g/day, for 4 days), piperacillin sulbactam, norepinephrine, diuretics, and milrinone.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 83,
                    "end": 84,
                    "mention": "1",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF0"
                }
            ],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Here we would like to raise several comments.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "In conclusion, this is a case of clinically suspected myocarditis of undefined aetiology (Viral due to known cardiotropic viruses? Transient unspecific myocardial injury and dysfunction during the hyperinflammatory state and cytokine storm? Immune-mediated?). Moreover, it was treated with an empirical 4-day course of methylprednisolone, which might in fact be detrimental both for COVID pneumonia4 and the clinically suspected COVID-associated myocarditis,2 and with IVIG that was neutral or useless for a hypothetical COVID myocarditis because IVIG do not contain IgG to COVID (normal blood donors, as the whole of the world\u2019s population are at present lacking a specific IgG response, except for recovered COVID patients). The favourable evolution seen in this case might simply reflect the curative strength of nature in a random association of COVID infection and clinically suspected acute myocarditis of undefined aetiology; up to 50% of acute myocarditis cases undergo spontaneous healing.2",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 398,
                    "end": 399,
                    "mention": "4",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF3"
                },
                {
                    "start": 458,
                    "end": 459,
                    "mention": "2",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF1"
                },
                {
                    "start": 998,
                    "end": 999,
                    "mention": "2",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF1"
                }
            ],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "\nConflict of interest: none declared.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
